	    <figcaption>ns blue light pulser for testing SK PMTs</figcaption>
	</figure>
		  	    
	<p>Hi, I'm Sara and I like to study fundamental physics. I develop hardware and software that help me do this. I'm a first year Ph.D. student at Princeton. Before that I worked on the <a href="http://www-sk.icrr.u-tokyo.ac.jp/sk/index-e.html">Super-Kamiokande</a> and <a href="http://www.hyperk.org/">Hyper-Kamiokande</a> collaborations at <a href="http://physics.bu.edu/sites/neutrino/news/">Boston University</a>. I searched for <a href="http://meetings.aps.org/Meeting/APR18/Session/C09.3/"> dinucleon and nucleon decay </a> (paper coming soon) and I helped develop front-end hardware for Hyper-K using <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/0911.0986"> these ASICs </a>. I also worked on Super-K High Voltage and solved related problems in the <a href="http://www-sk.icrr.u-tokyo.ac.jp/sk/detector/index-e.html">detector</a>. I have also worked on upgrades for the <a href="https://atlas.cern/discover/detector/muon-spectrometer">ATLAS muon spectrometer</a>, and I made a <a href ="http://muons.web.cern.ch/muons/">website</a> to monitor its detector elements.</p>

	<p> I've also done some other fun things, like attend <a href ="https://indico.fnal.gov/event/13429/">International Neutrino Summer School</a> at Fermilab.</p>

	<p> I'm still developing this webpage, so stay tuned. I plan to upload some of my projects and some physics resources you might like. </p>

